00:00:33.260 --> 00:00:35.750
So, just how bad is that for you?

00:00:35.750 --> 00:00:37.840
Should you wait it out to avoid embarrassment?

00:00:37.840 --> 00:00:40.950
Or should you bail on your prima’s 15th
birthday to relieve yourself?

00:00:40.950 --> 00:00:45.550
Well, it really depends, unless you’re literally
wearing Depends and then it doesn’t matter.

00:00:45.550 --> 00:00:49.870
The average adult pees about four to seven
times a day, because the average adult bladder

00:00:49.870 --> 00:00:54.030
can really only hold about sixteen ounces
worth of liquid before feeling the urge to

00:00:54.030 --> 00:00:55.030
purge.

00:00:55.030 --> 00:00:59.390
At night, your bladder can hold up to twice
that before signaling that you have to pee,

00:00:59.390 --> 00:01:03.150
which is why waking up to pee like a racehorse
is a pretty common experience.

00:01:03.150 --> 00:01:07.140
But every body is different, and the amount
of bladder fullness necessary to feel the

00:01:07.140 --> 00:01:11.640
pee reflect changes based on how hydrated
you are, the actual size of your bladder,

00:01:11.640 --> 00:01:13.960
and most importantly, your bladder sensitivity.

00:01:13.960 --> 00:01:19.060
See, when your bladder fills up, stretch receptors
along your bladder walls send a signal through

00:01:19.060 --> 00:01:21.110
your spinal cord up into your brain.

00:01:21.110 --> 00:01:25.600
In response, your brain sends back a “reflex”
signal, telling the detrusor muscle in your

00:01:25.600 --> 00:01:30.580
bladder to contract, which squeezes your bladder
and creates an even stronger stretch reflex.

00:01:30.580 --> 00:01:33.310
This feedback loop is what makes you have
to pee.

00:01:33.310 --> 00:01:36.620
Your internal bladder sphincter, which is
a muscle that is normally tightened against

00:01:36.620 --> 00:01:41.130
the intersection of your urethra and bladder,
opens up and is ready to let loose.

00:01:41.130 --> 00:01:44.920
But hold on a second, if that’s all there
was to it, we’d have no control over our

00:01:44.920 --> 00:01:45.920
urination.

00:01:45.920 --> 00:01:47.549
Luckily, there’s something in the way.

00:01:47.549 --> 00:01:51.490
The external sphincter, which is the last
line of defense against pee pants.

00:01:51.490 --> 00:01:55.229
As long as our external sphincter, also called
the “distal sphincter” is healthy and

00:01:55.229 --> 00:01:58.470
functional, you can technically hold your
pee forever.

00:01:58.470 --> 00:01:59.470
But you won’t.

00:01:59.470 --> 00:02:03.730
See, holding your pee in is kind of like an
unstoppable force going against an immovable

00:02:03.730 --> 00:02:04.730
object.

00:02:04.730 --> 00:02:09.640
Either your external sphincter or your detrusor
muscle are going to win the fight, and spoiler

00:02:09.640 --> 00:02:13.299
alert: unless you’ve had bladder cancer,
or bladder surgery, or if you’ve had a Radical

00:02:13.299 --> 00:02:16.900
Cystectomy with an Orthotopic Neobladder,
which is when doctors remove your bladder

00:02:16.900 --> 00:02:19.920
and replace it with a new one made out of
your small intestines… if none of those

00:02:19.920 --> 00:02:22.840
things apply to you, then your detrusor muscle
is going to win.

00:02:22.840 --> 00:02:24.599
You’re gonna pee alllll over yourself.

00:02:24.599 --> 00:02:28.959
