weak, it can rupture against the seal of your

00:02:28.959 --> 00:02:33.430
external sphincter, filling your abdomen with
urine that will have to be cathetered out.

00:02:33.430 --> 00:02:37.579
So if you’ve got a healthy bladder then
nothing to worry about except peeing yourself,

00:02:37.579 --> 00:02:38.579
right?

00:02:38.579 --> 00:02:39.579
Wrong.

00:02:39.579 --> 00:02:42.030
What you should be worried about are urinary
tract infections.

00:02:42.030 --> 00:02:46.069
See, instead of thinking of your bladder like
a five star hotel swimming lounge, it’s

00:02:46.069 --> 00:02:47.969
kind of more like a dirty pond.

00:02:47.969 --> 00:02:52.049
The longer you let the pond stagnate, the
more likely it is to build up bacteria, which

00:02:52.049 --> 00:02:54.470
can result in a urinary tract infection.

00:02:54.470 --> 00:02:57.000
That’s almost certainly E. coli.

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:00.620
And besides being an infection down there,
which is already unpleasant, it can also cause

00:03:00.620 --> 00:03:03.459
you to feel like you have to pee when your
bladder is empty!

00:03:03.459 --> 00:03:07.650
So, in a way, if you keep holding your pee,
you’ll end up feeling like you have to pee

00:03:07.650 --> 00:03:09.360
FOREVER!!!

00:03:09.360 --> 00:03:13.090
The other side effect of regularly holding
in your pee is called “urinary retention”

00:03:13.090 --> 00:03:16.989
which is when your detrusor muscle is unable
to fully evacuate the bladder.

00:03:16.989 --> 00:03:19.309
So every time you pee, you don’t get it
all out.

00:03:19.309 --> 00:03:24.190
Here’s the point: holding your pee is natural,
and we do it pretty much every single night.

00:03:24.190 --> 00:03:27.879
In any single case, for a healthy adult, holding
your pee isn’t too big of a deal, and in

00:03:27.879 --> 00:03:30.609
